WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:24.883 --> 01:27.884
(SCREAMING AND LAUGHING)

01:39.467 --> 01:41.426
MR. PLUMMER: What is going on in here?

01:43.550 --> 01:45.051
What is this mess?

01:47.883 --> 01:50.468
Didn't you all promise me
you were gonna be quiet?

01:51.217 --> 01:54.426
Melissa, put your phone away.
Put it away right now!

01:56.967 --> 01:58.134
What is this doing out?

02:01.466 --> 02:02.884
I asked you to be quiet.

02:04.050 --> 02:05.259
And look at you.

02:07.050 --> 02:08.258
Jacob, what is that?

02:10.466 --> 02:11.967
It's the sky, Mr. Plummer.

02:12.758 --> 02:14.342
MR. PLUMMER:
A green sky with yellow stars?

02:14.550 --> 02:16.009
It's Camp Jupiter's sky.

02:17.008 --> 02:18.259
Now, watch out, Jacob.

02:18.966 --> 02:20.884
Van Gogh ended up cutting off his own ear.

02:21.050 --> 02:22.051
(LAUGHING)

02:22.300 --> 02:24.301
Quiet. I said quiet, everybody!

02:26.383 --> 02:29.634
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

02:31.133 --> 02:32.551
WOMAN: Jake! Over here.

02:39.050 --> 02:40.051
Oh!

02:41.133 --> 02:43.592
Hey, hey, hey. Look at you.

02:45.216 --> 02:46.176
What happened?

02:46.633 --> 02:49.676
Your parents are going to be
coming home very late tonight.

02:50.341 --> 02:51.634
Come on, let's go.

02:52.508 --> 02:54.342
We'll pass by Papaya King on the way home.

02:54.550 --> 02:55.551
Yes.

02:58.675 --> 03:01.342
(PEN SCRATCHES)

03:12.966 --> 03:14.967
(PHONE RINGS)

03:21.133 --> 03:22.051
(PHONE BEEPS)

03:22.466 --> 03:23.926
Jardine residence, good evening.

03:24.383 --> 03:26.634
SAL: <i>Good evening.
And who am I talking to?</i>

03:27.466 --> 03:29.926
- Who is this?
- SAL: <i>This is Sal Bartolini.</i>

03:30.133 --> 03:32.134
<i>I'm an old friend of Max Jardine's.</i>

03:32.383 --> 03:34.676
- <i>Is this Jacob?</i>
- Yes.

03:34.966 --> 03:36.884
SAL: <i>Oh, Jacob, the last time I saw you,</i>

03:37.133 --> 03:40.259
<i>you were a little baby.
I guess you're all grown up now.</i>

03:41.133 --> 03:41.967
Mm.

03:42.966 --> 03:44.842
SAL: <i>Is your dad at home? Or your mom?</i>

03:45.300 --> 03:46.592
No, they're not home yet.

03:48.008 --> 03:51.092
SAL: <i>Look, I'm sorry to hear
about your grandfather, Jacob.</i>

03:51.341 --> 03:53.467
<i>Max and I knew each other for so long.</i>

03:53.883 --> 03:58.259
<i>We met when we were about your age.
You must be what, like, ten now?</i>

03:58.758 --> 03:59.717
Thirteen.

04:00.550 --> 04:03.884
SAL: <i>He was such a dear old friend
of mine, your granddaddy was.</i>

04:05.466 --> 04:07.426
<i>Do you know when the service is gonna be?</i>

04:07.883 --> 04:08.842
What service?

04:10.008 --> 04:11.259
SAL: <i>Well, the funeral.</i>

04:11.550 --> 04:14.051
<i>I imagine there's going
to be a service soon.</i>

04:17.341 --> 04:19.591
- Hold on a second.
- WOMAN: Who is it?

04:21.132 --> 04:22.176
I don't know.

04:24.508 --> 04:25.592
WOMAN: Can I help you?

04:34.383 --> 04:35.759
JAKE: Is that woman waiting for us?

04:36.216 --> 04:38.301
BRIAN: No, she rents the store downstairs.

04:43.216 --> 04:45.426
- (CAR DOOR CLOSES)
- (BELL RINGS)

04:45.633 --> 04:47.009
Antonio!

04:47.550 --> 04:49.634
JAKE: Are you and Dad serious
about us moving here?

04:50.050 --> 04:51.717
KATHY: Jake, let's talk about it later.

04:52.216 --> 04:54.134
I really don't wanna move to Brooklyn.

04:55.133 --> 04:57.676
Hi, Mrs. Calvelli, Brian Jardine.

04:57.883 --> 05:00.134
- We've met.
- Of course.

05:01.050 --> 05:03.551
I'm so sad for what has happened.

05:04.300 --> 05:05.134
I'm sorry.

05:05.883 --> 05:06.926
Thank you.

05:09.300 --> 05:10.467
I'm so sorry.

05:12.341 --> 05:14.426
Your father was a such a wonderful man.

05:16.216 --> 05:18.259
- He really was, you know.
- I know.

05:19.383 --> 05:20.342
ANTONIO: What do you want?

05:20.550 --> 05:23.426
- This is my son, Antonio.
- Hi.

05:23.841 --> 05:26.342
And I don't think
you've met my wife, Kathy.

05:27.550 --> 05:28.967
- Hi.
- Hello.

05:29.383 --> 05:32.467
- Nice to meet you. Leonor.
- I'm sorry, my hands are full.

05:32.883 --> 05:34.925
Yeah, we're just having
a little reception upstairs,

05:35.133 --> 05:37.842
- for some friends and family.
- Of course.

05:38.049 --> 05:39.675
BRIAN: You know, I grew up in this house.

05:40.049 --> 05:42.634
When I was a kid, there was
a produce store down here.

05:44.174 --> 05:46.092
LEONOR: I know, your father told me.

05:47.341 --> 05:49.342
- Let me help you with that.
- Oh, thanks.

05:51.549 --> 05:52.717
Ella the Harpy?

05:53.299 --> 05:56.509
She's a nerd, but I
got a thing for redheads. Don't you?

05:56.758 --> 05:58.342
Uh, I don't know.

06:00.966 --> 06:02.467
- I'll take it.
- Oh, thanks.

06:02.883 --> 06:05.509
- TONY: Tyson's such a douchebag.
- Oh, not in the end, he's not.

06:05.883 --> 06:07.425
I just finished <i>The Blood of Olympus.</i>

06:07.549 --> 06:09.050
TONY: I got the game. Wanna play?

06:09.591 --> 06:11.342
- Now?
- TONY: Yeah.

06:12.341 --> 06:15.467
I'd like to, but I can't.
It's my grandfather's funeral.

06:15.883 --> 06:17.009
TONY: Yeah, I know.

06:17.508 --> 06:19.342
I never know what to say
in these situations.

06:19.549 --> 06:23.092
JAKE: I think you're supposed to say,
"I'm sorry for your loss."

06:23.341 --> 06:24.175
TONY: That's it.

06:24.383 --> 06:25.967
- Here, could you carry this?
- TONY: Oh, yeah, sure.

06:26.508 --> 06:29.259
- Sorry for your loss.
- Oh, that's okay.

06:31.383 --> 06:32.509
TONY: Did you draw this?

06:33.299 --> 06:35.925
Yeah, it's the sky above Camp Jupiter,

06:36.174 --> 06:38.675
- the day of the battle.
- TONY: You're a real artist.

06:39.174 --> 06:40.092
Not really.

06:40.258 --> 06:42.092
TONY: Yeah, you are. This is awesome.

06:42.466 --> 06:44.509
- BRIAN: You got it, son?
- JAKE: Yeah, I got it.

06:46.341 --> 06:47.759
You know, you're gonna like
this neighborhood.

06:48.216 --> 06:52.009
- It's become a very bohemian area.
- JAKE: It's just a reception.

06:52.466 --> 06:55.384
TONY: I know, but if you
move in, I can show you around.

06:55.883 --> 06:57.675
My mom and I just live a few blocks away.

06:57.966 --> 06:59.592
JAKE: I'm not sure we're moving in.

07:01.008 --> 07:03.925
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

07:37.299 --> 07:38.634
- JAKE: Hi.
- LEONOR: Hello.

07:42.341 --> 07:46.509
It's a dessert we make in my country
for special occasions.

07:47.049 --> 07:48.009
I hope you like it.

07:48.299 --> 07:49.925
KATHY: Oh, my God, you didn't have to.

07:50.174 --> 07:52.467
LEONOR: Max loved this cake,
so I thought...

07:52.674 --> 07:55.092
KATHY: Come in, please.
You should come in.

07:55.299 --> 07:57.509
- LEONOR: It's okay.
- KATHY: No, please, I insist.

07:57.883 --> 07:59.509
LEONOR: I just wanted to bring the cake.

07:59.883 --> 08:03.717
I still have some paperwork
to do downstairs before I go home.

08:04.133 --> 08:05.175
KATHY: Thank you for this.

08:06.383 --> 08:09.217
Very kind of you. Thank you.

08:17.008 --> 08:18.509
WOMAN: Excuse us, but we're leaving.

08:18.883 --> 08:21.592
Oh, okay. Thank you, thank you so much.

08:22.008 --> 08:23.884
Thank you, thank you for coming.

08:24.299 --> 08:27.592
Thanks for coming. Thank you, thank you.

08:30.049 --> 08:32.260
- Okay. Bye.
- WOMAN: I'm so sorry.

08:32.383 --> 08:33.634
Oh, thank you so much.

08:33.883 --> 08:35.674
- Great to see you, thank you.
- WOMAN: It was lovely.

08:35.841 --> 08:37.009
BRIAN: Thank you, thank you.

08:38.049 --> 08:40.174
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

09:17.674 --> 09:21.800
(BRIAN SOBS)

10:16.049 --> 10:17.342
I don't remember this.

10:18.549 --> 10:19.800
Oh, my God.

10:20.882 --> 10:21.925
Her plate.

10:40.174 --> 10:43.092
(SEWING MACHINE WHIRS)

10:46.966 --> 10:47.967
Leonor.

10:49.299 --> 10:50.675
LEONOR: Hi, Kathy.

10:50.882 --> 10:52.092
(LATIN MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO)

10:52.549 --> 10:54.883
The boys are in my office in the back.

10:55.132 --> 10:56.925
No, look what I just found.

10:58.049 --> 10:59.258
My plate.

10:59.632 --> 11:03.550
KATHY: I think that night we just ended up
taking everything back to our old apartment.

11:04.132 --> 11:06.092
And we packed things away and I forgot.

11:06.341 --> 11:07.842
- (LEONOR CHUCKLES)
- I'm so sorry.

11:08.299 --> 11:09.800
No worries, please.

11:10.632 --> 11:11.842
It's a beautiful plate.

11:13.216 --> 11:14.842
Are you not working today?

11:15.382 --> 11:17.342
I don't see patients on Monday.

11:18.049 --> 11:19.342
I need a day a week...

11:20.216 --> 11:23.342
- to organize my life, you know?
- Good for you.

11:25.174 --> 11:26.550
The store looks cute.

11:27.882 --> 11:29.592
We are not doing so well.

11:30.882 --> 11:33.175
I like that dress, the green paisley.

11:34.132 --> 11:35.842
Oh, I love that one.

11:36.882 --> 11:40.258
- You should try that on.
- Oh, I have a lot to unpack.

11:40.466 --> 11:42.675
Come on, it'll take you a minute.

11:48.007 --> 11:50.842
- Perfection.
- Are you sure? I don't know.

11:51.549 --> 11:52.967
LEONOR: It looks great.

11:54.382 --> 11:56.092
Let me tie this.

11:58.174 --> 12:00.925
- The dress is beautiful.
- How much is it?

12:01.132 --> 12:03.633
Whatever the price is,
I'll give you ten percent discount.

12:04.049 --> 12:05.800
Let me see. Oh, no, up here.

12:06.549 --> 12:09.342
- Okay.
- Did you make this?

12:09.549 --> 12:11.133
No, not this one.

12:11.382 --> 12:13.925
But everything here is handmade designers.

12:14.174 --> 12:18.758
This is 250, and it's made
by a woman named Talita.

12:18.966 --> 12:20.717
She's Colombian, very talented.

12:23.507 --> 12:25.008
Guys, what do you think?

12:25.466 --> 12:27.008
(VIDEO GAME SOUNDS)

12:27.549 --> 12:28.550
KATHY: Jake?

12:29.632 --> 12:31.050
Jake, what's our deal?

12:31.632 --> 12:34.258
- Mom, I'm on vacation.
- KATHY: So?

12:34.882 --> 12:36.008
Dad said it was okay.

12:36.465 --> 12:38.925
We have this rule in the house,
no games during the week,

12:39.215 --> 12:40.925
and no internet before five either.

12:41.174 --> 12:44.591
But when they're on vacation,
they have all this free time.

12:45.007 --> 12:47.841
- What are you going to do?
- Shh, quiet!

12:48.299 --> 12:50.175
(IN SPANISH) Watch your tone, please.

12:51.549 --> 12:53.633
Mrs. Jardine, we're almost done
with this level.

12:53.882 --> 12:55.341
Can we have a few more moments, please?

12:55.549 --> 12:56.841
LEONOR: That's better.

12:57.215 --> 12:59.091
KATHY: Sure, you can finish this level.

12:59.299 --> 13:00.800
But first you gotta tell me,
what do you think?

13:01.132 --> 13:02.008
The dress.

13:02.215 --> 13:04.008
TONY: Great. I actually
thought it was yours.

13:04.507 --> 13:08.133
- Jake?
- Love it. Love the feathers.

13:08.632 --> 13:10.591
(KATHY LAUGHS)

13:11.632 --> 13:14.133
(VIDEO GAME SOUNDS CONTINUE)

13:27.174 --> 13:28.300
What are you writing?

13:31.549 --> 13:34.758
Nothing much,
only an idea that occurred to me.

13:36.382 --> 13:38.008
An idea for a short story.

13:39.340 --> 13:42.341
A young girl grows up on
the shores of a lake, as you have.

13:43.382 --> 13:45.425
She loves the lake as the gulls do,

13:46.382 --> 13:48.841
and she is as happy and as free
as they are.

13:50.215 --> 13:51.466
DIRECTOR: And then here you can counter.

13:51.840 --> 13:52.966
But a man sees her...

13:54.382 --> 13:59.966
who happens to come her way,
and he destroys her out of idleness,

14:00.882 --> 14:02.716
as this gull here has been destroyed.

14:03.299 --> 14:05.133
DIRECTOR: Okay, good, what are
you saying to her right now?

14:05.382 --> 14:06.425
That's lovely, I love that.

14:06.632 --> 14:08.341
But what are you saying to her,
do you think?

14:09.632 --> 14:10.591
Where is it?

14:15.049 --> 14:16.925
BRIAN: Why don't you come and
help me prepare dinner tonight?

14:17.465 --> 14:18.341
Where's Mom?

14:18.549 --> 14:20.550
BRIAN: Your mother had
an emergency with a patient.

14:20.965 --> 14:22.341
She's not gonna be home 'til tonight.

14:22.549 --> 14:25.258
- Another suicide?
- BRIAN: Jake!

14:29.340 --> 14:30.841
JAKE: Dad, I can't find my drawings.

14:31.382 --> 14:34.175
What drawings? Help me cut these.

14:35.132 --> 14:37.091
The series I made on Percy Jackson.

14:37.882 --> 14:39.925
- <i>The Sea of Monsters.</i>
- BRIAN: Those old drawings?

14:40.340 --> 14:41.300
Yes.

14:42.382 --> 14:43.716
BRIAN: Did you look in the trunk?

14:44.049 --> 14:45.675
Yes, Dad, I looked. They're not there.

14:45.882 --> 14:48.633
BRIAN: Well, I don't know, Jake,
maybe they got thrown away.

14:49.382 --> 14:51.675
Why would you do that?
They're my drawings!

14:52.174 --> 14:53.508
Why don't you just make new ones?

14:53.965 --> 14:56.300
'Cause new ones are never
gonna be like the old ones.

14:56.549 --> 14:58.383
Jake, we moved.

14:59.132 --> 15:00.716
We got rid of furniture.

15:01.049 --> 15:02.841
We threw away clothes, gave away books.

15:03.132 --> 15:05.508
- We got a new apartment.
- So?

15:06.299 --> 15:09.841
Hey, let me tell you something.
It's good to get rid of stuff.

15:10.132 --> 15:12.466
It's a little hard at first,
but then it feels really good.

15:14.049 --> 15:15.591
Just gotta learn to let go.

15:19.049 --> 15:24.008
BRIAN: I play Trigorin, a celebrated
writer and the boyfriend of a...

15:25.299 --> 15:26.800
famous actress...

15:28.049 --> 15:28.925
Arkadina.

15:29.882 --> 15:32.966
There's also Nina,
who is the neighbor's daughter,

15:33.549 --> 15:35.091
and she wants to be an actress.

15:35.340 --> 15:37.716
And at first we think
she's in love with Konstantin.

15:37.965 --> 15:40.425
She ends up having an affair
with my character, Trigorin.

15:40.965 --> 15:42.175
JAKE: Sounds complicated.

15:43.132 --> 15:46.341
Mm. Well, it's complex.

15:47.382 --> 15:51.425
But it's also unexpected.
It has a lot of humor in it, too.

15:52.882 --> 15:53.925
What part?

15:57.340 --> 15:58.674
(DOOR OPENS)

15:59.465 --> 16:01.883
Good. You're already eating.

16:04.548 --> 16:06.424
- JAKE: Hi, Mom.
- BRIAN: How was it?

16:07.048 --> 16:09.591
KATHY: Fine. She's doing good.

16:11.465 --> 16:13.174
The problem now is her husband.

16:16.382 --> 16:19.174
The last thing I want to do
right now is talk about work.

16:19.465 --> 16:21.174
I was telling Jake about the new play.

16:21.382 --> 16:22.716
I'm starving.

16:23.048 --> 16:25.424
JAKE: I thought you weren't working
with the train anymore.

16:26.132 --> 16:27.758
I thought you were gonna do Broadway now.

16:28.882 --> 16:30.133
It's not that simple.

16:30.632 --> 16:33.424
You said you weren't doing
this non-profit stuff.

16:33.882 --> 16:36.841
That the strategy was
to reach a wider audience.

16:37.048 --> 16:38.258
Things have changed.

16:38.465 --> 16:40.633
You should applaud your father
for being adaptable.

16:41.007 --> 16:42.174
It's what life's all about.

16:45.757 --> 16:48.508
(KIDS SHOUTING)

16:52.048 --> 16:54.008
- Hey, Tony! We need one more!
- TONY: I can't.

16:54.215 --> 16:56.133
- Why can't you?
- I gotta get home.

17:01.548 --> 17:03.091
Watch out, Katy Perry!

17:57.048 --> 17:58.924
(SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

17:59.173 --> 18:01.174
TONY: Twelve minutes and 23 seconds!

18:02.215 --> 18:05.924
From Jake's house to here
in 12 minutes and 23 seconds.

18:07.215 --> 18:08.591
JAKE: Good afternoon, Mrs. Calvelli.

18:09.048 --> 18:10.174
LEONOR: Hi, Jake.

18:12.215 --> 18:14.258
(IN SPANISH)
You haven't said hello, Mister.

18:14.965 --> 18:16.299
- Hello, Hernán.
- <i>Hola.</i>

18:16.548 --> 18:19.424
That's my friend Jacob Jardine,
but we call him Jake.

18:19.882 --> 18:21.258
- Hello there, Jake.
- Hi.

18:23.132 --> 18:26.633
- Jake, Hernán.
- So you're the grandson?

18:28.298 --> 18:30.716
Yes, Max was his grandfather,

18:31.048 --> 18:33.924
and his father is Brian Jardine.

18:34.548 --> 18:36.591
(IN SPANISH)
The one I was telling you about.

18:37.007 --> 18:39.258
Yeah, he's an actor.
And my mom's a psychotherapist.

18:39.465 --> 18:42.716
HERNÁN: Huh. So how are you enjoying
Brooklyn so far?

18:43.298 --> 18:45.508
JAKE: I like it a lot. Yeah, it's...

18:45.965 --> 18:49.966
It's a lot more peaceful than Manhattan,
and we have much more space. It's great.

18:51.340 --> 18:54.091
So are you going to be an actor?
Like your father?

18:54.340 --> 18:55.341
JAKE: I don't know.

18:56.382 --> 18:57.966
HERNÁN: Well, you look like an artist.

18:58.965 --> 19:00.508
The long hair, everything.

19:01.048 --> 19:02.049
Maybe.

19:02.965 --> 19:06.091
He'll tell us more later,
right, Jake? Go ahead.

19:06.298 --> 19:08.174
- Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you, too.

19:10.215 --> 19:12.041
(IN SPANISH) So, that's the son.

19:24.382 --> 19:26.341
(VIDEO GAME SOUNDS)

19:26.632 --> 19:29.132
Hey, your dad any good at acting?

19:30.173 --> 19:31.632
I don't know. Maybe.

19:32.298 --> 19:34.966
I thought if he was, he maybe
could gimme a couple pointers,

19:35.215 --> 19:36.924
'cause I wanna be an actor when I grow up.

19:38.006 --> 19:39.757
Oh, sure, yeah, I guess.

19:40.298 --> 19:42.591
He's not that successful or anything.

19:44.298 --> 19:47.341
My dream is to go to LaGuardia
High School for Performing Arts.

19:47.631 --> 19:48.716
You heard of that school?

19:50.215 --> 19:52.174
Well, you know, Nicki Minaj went there...

19:53.340 --> 19:56.007
Al Pacino, but he flunked out, so...

19:57.965 --> 20:00.382
Yeah, I think my dad applied there.

20:01.048 --> 20:03.466
Oh, really? Well, it's my dream school.

20:04.215 --> 20:08.257
I've been looking around for some theater
classes, you know, been practicing on my own.

20:08.715 --> 20:10.466
Gonna audition next year
for the ninth grade.

20:12.881 --> 20:14.966
It's gonna be a lot of work
and a lot of practice.

20:15.215 --> 20:16.591
I might need a partner, okay?

20:17.006 --> 20:19.507
- But I'm not an actor.
- That's okay, can you read?

20:20.548 --> 20:22.091
These are some of the scripts
I'm working on.

20:22.340 --> 20:25.341
Like <i>Ah, Wilderness!</i> and <i>Pariah</i>
by August Strindberg.

20:26.548 --> 20:29.174
It's perfect for us to work on,
'cause it's just two guys.

20:31.340 --> 20:35.174
You know what? Focus on your art more,
maybe we could both go to LaGuardia together.

20:35.381 --> 20:36.591
Wouldn't that be great?

20:39.215 --> 20:42.341
- I guess I can try.
- That's the spirit.

20:47.131 --> 20:50.841
- Is Hernán your mom's boyfriend?
- That's disgusting, no!

20:51.215 --> 20:52.507
He's a friend from Chile.

20:53.881 --> 20:58.091
My parents are married.
They just don't live together.

20:59.131 --> 21:01.257
- I don't understand.
- (SCOFFS) Me neither.

21:02.465 --> 21:05.674
My dad travels a lot.
He's a nurse who works for the UN.

21:06.173 --> 21:07.091
Where is he now?

21:07.340 --> 21:09.132
TONY: He's in Angola, it's in Africa.

21:10.048 --> 21:11.174
Look what he sent me.

21:13.881 --> 21:15.424
JAKE: Do you miss having him around more?

21:17.048 --> 21:21.591
I used to. But it's been a while now,
so I've gotten used to it.

21:22.006 --> 21:25.507
Yeah, sometimes my dad goes away
if he's shooting a movie.

21:26.048 --> 21:28.424
But it hasn't really happened in a while.

21:28.881 --> 21:29.841
TONY: Found it.

21:31.548 --> 21:34.632
My dad said he's gonna take me on safari,
and these are the animals we're gonna see.

21:36.465 --> 21:37.716
That's really cool.

21:40.381 --> 21:42.007
Do you wish they still lived together?

21:42.631 --> 21:45.507
