he'll cook porchetta.

21:45.715 --> 21:47.174
It's like a roast pork butt.

21:48.048 --> 21:49.466
That's... (LAUGHS)

21:49.881 --> 21:51.341
- It's good.
- That's disgusting.

21:51.548 --> 21:55.007
It's good. We sit at the table,
you know, just the three of us,

21:55.215 --> 21:57.716
and my dad will tell us
about people he met,

21:58.006 --> 22:00.674
places he's been,
and stories about Africa.

22:01.298 --> 22:03.174
We seem like a normal family, and then...

22:03.381 --> 22:04.716
(CLICKS FINGERS) Boom.

22:05.131 --> 22:07.424
They start fighting about
something stupid, like always.

22:08.298 --> 22:09.424
And...

22:10.506 --> 22:12.591
I realize it's better
when he's not around.

22:14.381 --> 22:17.799
JAKE: Imagine if your mom
went with you on the safari,

22:18.548 --> 22:20.507
and they ended up falling in love again.

22:20.965 --> 22:23.007
There's a very little chance
of that happening.

22:23.215 --> 22:26.591
JAKE: But just imagine.
You get an envelope one day.

22:27.340 --> 22:30.591
You open it, and it's
two tickets to a safari.

22:31.048 --> 22:32.716
One for you and one for your mom.

22:33.173 --> 22:37.591
And she decides to go because
she feels like she needs a vacation.

22:38.631 --> 22:42.091
So when you get to Africa,
your dad picks you up at the airport,

22:42.715 --> 22:45.007
and takes you to this incredible place,

22:45.298 --> 22:47.841
like... Like this picture here.

22:48.631 --> 22:52.591
You see lions and elephants, giraffes.

22:54.048 --> 22:57.091
And then it's the end of a beautiful
day in the African savannah.

22:58.006 --> 23:01.132
Your dad wants to take you up
this big hill to see the sunset,

23:01.339 --> 23:06.340
but you're too tired, so you just say
you're gonna rest in your hotel room.

23:08.214 --> 23:11.299
So they go, the two of them alone.

23:12.548 --> 23:17.174
And when they get to the top,
the colors of the sky is like...

23:18.048 --> 23:19.757
Like nothing they've ever seen before.

23:21.298 --> 23:23.132
A green sky with yellow stars.

23:45.506 --> 23:48.465
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

24:02.006 --> 24:04.590
TONY: Mami! Can I stay for dinner
tonight with the Jardines?

24:05.048 --> 24:06.465
- LEONOR: Hmm?
- Mami!

24:06.881 --> 24:08.632
Can I stay for dinner tonight
with the Jardines?

24:09.131 --> 24:10.715
- They're having hamburgers.
- JAKE: And hot dogs.

24:11.339 --> 24:15.924
(IN SPANISH) Antonio, we have dinner at home,
and I can't come pick you up later.

24:16.673 --> 24:19.090
And I don't like you
walking home alone at night.

24:19.298 --> 24:20.840
JAKE: Well, he could sleep over.

24:21.506 --> 24:23.590
Have you spoken to your father about this?

24:24.006 --> 24:25.965
- JAKE: He won't mind.
- Sure?

24:35.048 --> 24:36.840
- Dad?
- Jake, yes.

24:37.048 --> 24:39.840
- Can Tony sleep over tonight?
- Uh...

24:41.381 --> 24:42.507
Hello, Leonor.

24:43.548 --> 24:44.507
LEONOR: Hi.

24:45.048 --> 24:47.549
- You've met my sister Audrey?
- Oh, yes, of course.

24:47.964 --> 24:49.757
Hi, Leonor, long time no see.

24:50.173 --> 24:53.590
Jake is asking if Tony
can stay for dinner.

24:54.006 --> 24:55.090
JAKE: And a sleep-over.

24:55.298 --> 24:59.090
Yeah, because after dinner, it's gonna
be too late for him to walk home alone.

24:59.339 --> 25:01.674
Tony, you wanna have hot dogs
and hamburgers with us tonight?

25:01.964 --> 25:03.465
- TONY: Yes!
- That is a done deal.

25:03.631 --> 25:04.590
TONY: Yes!

25:07.881 --> 25:09.590
I just wanted to make sure with you.

25:10.006 --> 25:14.840
BRIAN: No, no, no, please, I can't tell you
how happy I am that Jake has a new friend.

25:15.131 --> 25:17.674
You know, it's not easy with him
and other boys, and...

25:19.048 --> 25:20.757
Great that the two of 'em
get along so well.

25:21.006 --> 25:22.174
- Yeah.
- You have a great kid there,

25:22.464 --> 25:23.674
but I guess you know that.

25:23.881 --> 25:26.174
(CHUCKLES) Thanks.

25:26.464 --> 25:28.340
Leonor, do you want some wine?

25:29.881 --> 25:32.424
You know, Brian and I wanted
to have a talk with you

25:32.631 --> 25:35.840
about some things anyway,
so maybe now's a good time?

25:36.381 --> 25:38.632
Oh, thank you, but...

25:39.173 --> 25:43.424
I have to go back and finish
some stuff at the office.

25:44.464 --> 25:47.632
Well, we just wanted a minute
of your time, if that's okay.

25:47.839 --> 25:48.757
Right, Brian?

25:49.006 --> 25:51.174
LEONOR: I have to go back, but thanks.

25:51.548 --> 25:55.132
You know, Leonor,
ever since my father died...

25:56.048 --> 25:57.090
just so much has happened.

25:57.381 --> 25:59.590
You and I haven't really had
a chance to talk about the store

26:00.048 --> 26:02.674
and all that stuff, and...

26:03.214 --> 26:05.507
maybe we could just have a chat this week?

26:06.298 --> 26:09.840
Oh, I'm sorry, but this week
is not good for me.

26:10.131 --> 26:13.174
- I'm doing inventory, so...
- Next week?

26:14.173 --> 26:17.799
- Could be.
- Thursday I have rehearsal.

26:18.048 --> 26:19.424
We're gonna get out of rehearsal early.

26:19.631 --> 26:21.090
I could come by early evening?

26:22.131 --> 26:24.424
- Sure.
- Great.

26:34.297 --> 26:35.840
Come on, guys, burgers'll get cold.

26:36.464 --> 26:38.465
The truth is that
the neighborhood is changing

26:38.672 --> 26:41.590
and that's a very old-fashioned store.

26:42.047 --> 26:44.257
She did complain to me
that business is not so good.

26:44.506 --> 26:47.715
Well, of course she's gonna say that.
The contract's up.

26:48.172 --> 26:52.423
My guy told me that a similar space
like that in this area could get...

26:54.214 --> 26:56.132
- Five thousand.
- That's crazy.

26:56.381 --> 26:59.340
- Cheese, mustard and ketchup, please.
- Guests first. Tony, what do you want?

26:59.672 --> 27:02.840
I'll have avocados, tomatoes,
onions, cheese and ketchup.

27:03.131 --> 27:04.423
AUDREY: Yeah, that's on the low end.

27:04.631 --> 27:06.340
- KATHY: What's the number now?
- BRIAN: Eleven hundred.

27:06.839 --> 27:08.465
For eight years? Never an increase?

27:08.756 --> 27:11.423
Maybe we can talk about this
a little later.

27:13.006 --> 27:16.298
Tony, did I hear your father
lives in Africa?

27:16.964 --> 27:21.173
Yeah, in Angola. It's a small
Portuguese colony in Africa.

27:21.547 --> 27:22.965
I wrote a paper on it last year.

27:23.214 --> 27:25.340
I got a B+, which was
actually pretty good because

27:25.547 --> 27:27.090
I only spent, like, an hour on it.

27:28.214 --> 27:29.507
My teachers, they're whack, you know.

27:29.839 --> 27:32.007
They'll give you a good grade
on something and you don't try,

27:32.214 --> 27:35.132
but when you really work hard
and put your best effort into it,

27:35.381 --> 27:36.423
they'll give you a bad grade.

27:37.839 --> 27:39.840
TONY: Can you pass the ketchup?
I always like a lot of ketchup.

27:40.381 --> 27:41.382
Thanks.

28:00.672 --> 28:03.340
(SUBWAY PASSES)

29:03.464 --> 29:06.757
Jump up! Jump up! Use your voice!

29:07.047 --> 29:09.673
(SHOUTING)

29:09.964 --> 29:11.507
You're a tree in the forest.

29:15.964 --> 29:17.173
And it's snowing!

29:18.131 --> 29:19.007
(GIRL SHIVERS)

29:19.297 --> 29:22.507
You're the worst dancer in the world,
and you think you're wonderful! Go!

29:22.964 --> 29:23.840
Yeah!

29:25.172 --> 29:27.465
Give it sounds! Give it sounds!

29:28.047 --> 29:30.590
(STUDENTS MAKE NOISES)

29:31.381 --> 29:34.090
I'm going to introduce you
to a new relaxation exercise.

29:34.297 --> 29:37.173
I'd like all the chairs facing this way.

29:38.172 --> 29:40.423
And with plenty... No, this way!

29:40.714 --> 29:41.840
(STUDENTS MOANING)

29:42.131 --> 29:44.965
WOMAN: Stop yelling, okay? Really...

29:45.214 --> 29:46.840
TEACHER: Keep your throat relaxed!

29:47.047 --> 29:48.465
(SCREAMING)

29:48.881 --> 29:52.840
(ARGUING)

29:53.214 --> 29:55.132
The genesis of acting is seeing.

29:57.047 --> 29:58.340
Observation.

29:59.172 --> 30:03.715
Understanding what makes behavior, yes?

30:05.630 --> 30:08.048
So when we do the repetition exercise,

30:08.297 --> 30:12.340
that person does it to us.
We simply react, yes?

30:13.380 --> 30:14.340
So...

30:14.880 --> 30:17.090
Start the exercise, take your time.

30:17.297 --> 30:18.298
GIRL: You're wearing a pretty shirt.

30:18.880 --> 30:21.256
- I'm wearing a pretty shirt.
- You're wearing a pretty shirt.

30:21.505 --> 30:23.423
- Do you like my shirt?
- (CLAPS) No, no.

30:24.964 --> 30:27.423
No questions! Observations.

30:27.964 --> 30:30.090
- You seem mad.
- GIRL: I seem mad.

30:30.297 --> 30:32.840
- You seem mad.
- GIRL: (SCOFFS) I seem mad.

30:33.047 --> 30:34.590
- You seem mad.
- GIRL: You seem mad.

30:35.005 --> 30:37.090
- I like your hair.
- I like my hair.

30:37.297 --> 30:39.923
- BOY: I like your hair.
- I like my hair.

30:41.130 --> 30:42.840
How long have you been doing
this exercise?

30:43.547 --> 30:47.256
How long you been doing this exercise?

30:47.505 --> 30:48.840
TONY: How long have you
been doing this exercise?

30:49.047 --> 30:50.631
- I'm not playing with you!
- I'm not playing with you!

30:50.964 --> 30:55.006
You know, you make me make mistakes
in my own exercise!

30:55.214 --> 30:58.340
You make me make mistakes
in my own exercise!

30:58.547 --> 31:01.006
- I make you make mistakes!
- I make you make mistakes!

31:01.214 --> 31:03.256
- I make you make mistakes!
- I make you make mistakes!

31:03.505 --> 31:06.298
I make this exercise the way I like it!

31:06.547 --> 31:09.131
I make the exercise the way I like it!

31:09.380 --> 31:11.006
- I like the exercise!
- I like the exercise!

31:11.214 --> 31:15.841
- I love the exercise!
- I love this exercise!

31:15.964 --> 31:18.465
I don't wanna do any other exercise!

31:18.672 --> 31:21.090
- I don't wanna do another exercise!
- I don't wanna do another exercise!

31:21.297 --> 31:24.923
- I never wanna do another exercise!
- I never wanna do another exercise!

31:25.172 --> 31:27.923
- You have a terrible attitude!
- You've got a terrible attitude!

31:28.172 --> 31:30.673
- You have a terrible attitude!
- You have a terrible attitude!

31:30.880 --> 31:34.673
Your attitude is more horrible than mine!

31:34.880 --> 31:38.801
- You're a master of horrible attitudes!
- You're a master of master horrible!

31:38.945 --> 31:42.256
You've got the Swiss cheese
up inside your skull instead of a brain!

31:42.505 --> 31:44.923
I got Swiss cheese inside of
my skull instead of a brain!

31:45.172 --> 31:47.006
I don't know how you get
anything done all day long!

31:47.214 --> 31:48.715
I don't know how I get
anything done all day long!

31:48.964 --> 31:52.135
- I don't know how you get anything done!
- I don't know how you get all the day done.

31:52.279 --> 31:54.586
- I don't know what you're talking about.
- I don't know what you're talking about.

31:54.714 --> 31:59.631
- You never know what you're talking about.
- I never know what I'm talking about.

32:00.005 --> 32:01.715
You're gonna make me ask another
question, aren't you?

32:01.964 --> 32:03.090
I'm gonna make you ask another question.

32:03.214 --> 32:05.298
- There you are, you did it again!
- I did it again!

32:05.464 --> 32:08.215
- I did it again!
- I did it again!

32:08.464 --> 32:09.381
- You did it again!
- You did it!

32:09.630 --> 32:10.798
- You did it again!
- You!

32:11.047 --> 32:12.673
- You! You! You!
- You! You! You!

32:13.047 --> 32:14.006
- You did it!
- You did it!

32:14.214 --> 32:15.131
- You did it!
- I didn't do it!

32:15.380 --> 32:17.173
- Get outta my face!
- Get outta my face!

32:17.464 --> 32:19.090
- Get outta my face!
- Get out of my face!

32:19.297 --> 32:21.840
Get out of my face!

32:22.297 --> 32:24.840
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

32:27.797 --> 32:29.006
GIRL: Oh! Something in my eye...

32:30.089 --> 32:31.465
GIRL 2: See, it's right there. Look!

32:32.380 --> 32:33.423
There!

32:33.964 --> 32:35.340
(LAUGHING)

32:35.922 --> 32:37.506
GIRL: Please, put him in a closet.

32:37.880 --> 32:39.048
GIRL 2: Trust fall. Fall.

32:39.297 --> 32:41.715
- First, you have to kill him.
- Fall into me. Fall into me.

32:43.464 --> 32:44.756
- (TONY GROANS)
- (LAUGHING)

32:49.380 --> 32:51.506
- Miles was like, "How are you?"
- Yeah.

32:51.839 --> 32:54.048
GIRL: Oh, my God, yes. Miles started it.

32:54.214 --> 32:56.173
- Miles...
- No. 'Cause she said hi to him once,

32:56.380 --> 33:00.048
so he said "hi" back,
and she got into the conversation...

33:00.214 --> 33:01.215
GIRL: Exactly.

33:01.339 --> 33:04.298
TONY: And then she re-used my words
against me. And then...

33:04.839 --> 33:06.923
GIRL: She put words into my mouth.
She was saying...

33:09.714 --> 33:11.590
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

33:12.297 --> 33:14.131
(ALL LAUGHING)

33:19.422 --> 33:21.381
Oh, my God.
And I wanted to change it, but...

33:32.338 --> 33:33.256
COACH: Let's go!

33:33.505 --> 33:35.173
- BOY: Right here!
- COACH: Go, go, go!

33:35.463 --> 33:36.464
Donny!

33:37.505 --> 33:38.589
- Keep going!
- BOY: Back!

33:40.297 --> 33:42.589
- BOY: Good save.
- SECOND BOY: Nice one, Tony!

33:48.338 --> 33:50.923
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

33:55.838 --> 33:58.589
Hey, Umar, we should try
that thing that the Brazilian does.

33:58.963 --> 34:00.881
So you look like you're gonna
pass it to one player,

34:01.130 --> 34:02.339
but you actually pass it
to the other side.

34:02.547 --> 34:04.589
That actually might be a good
idea, if you came to practice.

34:04.797 --> 34:05.756
What are you talking about?

34:05.963 --> 34:07.506
Dude, you didn't even show up
last Saturday.

34:07.755 --> 34:09.339
Because Tony has a new boyfriend now.

34:09.547 --> 34:10.339
(LAUGHING)

34:10.630 --> 34:13.464
Ask your sister if she thinks I'm the type
to have a boyfriend. She'll know.

34:15.380 --> 34:18.089
- JOEY: My cousin Allen goes to 342.
- So what?

34:18.297 --> 34:20.839
- JOEY: That's his school, isn't it?
- What are you talking about?

34:21.130 --> 34:23.547
Little Jake. My cousin goes to his school.

34:23.963 --> 34:26.089
- They say he's a weirdo.
- TONY: Shut up, Joey!

34:26.297 --> 34:28.922
They say he draws dresses
for the girls during recess.

34:31.880 --> 34:33.422
- Give that back!
- TONY: There you are, go ahead.

34:33.630 --> 34:34.464
Eat it!

34:37.630 --> 34:39.464
(STUDENTS SHOUT)

34:42.172 --> 34:43.964
ALL: <i>Fight! Fight! Fight! Fight! Fight!</i>

34:48.463 --> 34:49.797
MR. PLUMMER: <i>"...and the stars never rise,</i>

34:50.005 --> 34:53.005
<i>but I feel the bright eyes
of the beautiful Annabel Lee.</i>

34:53.880 --> 34:57.464
<i>And so, all the night-tide,
I lie down by the side</i>

34:58.213 --> 35:02.964
<i>of my darling, my darling
my life and my bride."</i>

35:03.547 --> 35:04.923
What's he saying there?

35:05.172 --> 35:07.006
What's he talking about when he says that?

35:07.880 --> 35:11.089
I think that his love, kind of
like what they were saying,

35:11.297 --> 35:15.006
he's imagining her
in his mind and his heart

35:15.213 --> 35:18.131
because he loves her that much,
like, he's able to...

35:19.047 --> 35:23.298
like, create a version of her
in his heart because...

35:23.547 --> 35:25.173
MR. PLUMMER: Or it could even be literal.

35:26.172 --> 35:28.798
I mean, he may actually,
several times a week,

35:29.338 --> 35:32.798
go down and spend the day
lying next to her in her grave.

35:34.297 --> 35:39.006
So what I want you to do for your
assignment is try to write a poem.

35:40.047 --> 35:44.298
Not try, but do it. Write a poem
about someone you love.

35:44.547 --> 35:47.673
Okay? It'll be fun.
Or at least, make it fun.

35:48.380 --> 35:49.589
That's your assignment.

35:50.755 --> 35:51.589
(DOOR OPENS)

35:51.838 --> 35:52.798
- Hi.
- JAKE: Hi.

35:56.172 --> 35:58.256
- Hi, Leonor.
- LEONOR: Hi, Jake.

35:58.963 --> 36:00.173
Where are you going?

36:01.130 --> 36:05.756
- Is Tony in the office?
- He is, and he's staying there.

36:06.130 --> 36:07.423
He's helping me out today.

36:07.630 --> 36:09.256
But we're supposed to meet some friends.

36:10.172 --> 36:12.506
Are those the same friends
that beat him up?

36:13.338 --> 36:14.923
- What?
- LEONOR: That's right.

36:16.172 --> 36:17.298
They beat him up.

36:18.963 --> 36:20.423
And you should ask him why.

36:25.297 --> 36:26.256
TONY: What's up?

36:26.547 --> 36:28.173
- What happened?
- TONY: Nothing.

36:28.380 --> 36:31.006
- I bumped into Joey at soccer.
- JAKE: But your mom said that...

36:31.213 --> 36:34.006
She's so dramatic.
She deserves an Academy Award.

36:35.047 --> 36:36.298
She doesn't want me to go out with you

36:36.547 --> 36:39.089
'cause she wants me
to help her with this. Look.

36:39.338 --> 36:40.714
She's not good with numbers, you know?

36:42.047 --> 36:43.506
Go ahead, I'll meet up with you later.

36:45.213 --> 36:46.173
Okay.

37:22.130 --> 37:25.756
BRIAN: I'm so sorry, Leonor.
Our rehearsal went late.

37:25.963 --> 37:27.881
- Is this still a good time?
- LEONOR: Yeah.

37:28.296 --> 37:31.714
I sent the girl home early
so we could talk.

37:33.130 --> 37:34.131
You wanna go in?

37:34.380 --> 37:36.714
- I'm just going to finish this.
- Okay.

37:42.546 --> 37:44.797
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

37:52.338 --> 37:55.089
(SHUTTERS CLOSE)

38:00.880 --> 38:03.422
- The store looks nice.
- LEONOR: Thanks.

38:06.130 --> 38:08.339
Brian, why don't you sit down?

38:11.463 --> 38:12.422
BRIAN: My...

38:13.296 --> 38:17.339
sister and I were working
on a transfer of ownership.

38:17.963 --> 38:19.089
It's...

38:20.046 --> 38:21.172
It's almost done.

38:21.630 --> 38:26.339
My father left everything in order,
the taxes and all of that.

38:26.671 --> 38:30.089
The only thing still pending
is the store, which needs a lease.

38:30.963 --> 38:34.339
You know, your father never
thought much about contracts.

38:34.671 --> 38:37.256
And he was very happy to have me here.

38:38.046 --> 38:41.089
Max thought my store gave
glamour to the neighborhood,

38:41.505 --> 38:44.464
and he was proud to be associated.

38:44.963 --> 38:46.339
Well, the neighborhood's changing.

38:47.880 --> 38:51.422
I'm sure you've noticed the rents have
gone up a lot in the last couple of years.

38:51.880 --> 38:56.256
Yeah, I noticed, and so did Max.

38:56.505 --> 38:59.339
But it was his desire that I stay here.

39:01.046 --> 39:02.839
BRIAN: Well, we don't want you to go away.

39:03.880 --> 39:05.881
My sister has worked up a new lease.

39:06.338 --> 39:09.797
We think it's very fair.
It's not market price.

39:10.213 --> 39:12.839
We know that's not even possible but,

39:13.380 --> 39:15.422
still, you can't expect
to pay the same amounts

39:15.630 --> 39:17.339
that you did when you first moved in.

39:17.546 --> 39:19.256
Here, just take a look at this.

39:19.463 --> 39:23.006
Before we go any further
with this conversation,

39:23.380 --> 39:25.672
I want you to take a look at this.

39:27.463 --> 39:30.589
I am probably the last person to have

39:31.380 --> 39:33.922
photos printed the old-fashioned way.

39:34.380 --> 39:39.672
It's completely different than seeing them
on a cell phone, don't you agree?

39:40.130 --> 39:44.256
That's me in the backyard, on July fourth.

39:44.880 --> 39:45.922
Mm.

39:46.296 --> 39:50.714
That's me, Tony and Max
at the Saint Anthony's fair.

39:52.296 --> 39:56.839
That's us with my family,
when they came to visit.

39:58.963 --> 40:01.631
Your father and I were very good friends.

40:02.463 --> 40:05.631
We spent a lot of time together.

40:06.380 --> 40:09.172
What you and your sister don't understand

40:09.630 --> 40:12.089
is that your father
wanted me to stay here.

40:12.671 --> 40:16.506
He thought of me as part of
this house, of this neighborhood.

40:20.213 --> 40:24.839
I was more his family,
if you want to know, than you were.

40:29.046 --> 40:30.964
Well, that's a ridiculous thing to say.

40:31.546 --> 40:35.339
You hardly talked to each other.
You never came to visit.

40:35.796 --> 40:39.089
I was the one here. I saw him every day.

40:39.296 --> 40:40.630
This is not what I came here for.

40:40.879 --> 40:42.922
Just, please, take a look
at the lease, okay?

40:43.171 --> 40:45.172
Let's just get back to that.
It's very fair.

40:46.379 --> 40:47.589
I don't need to.

40:49.046 --> 40:53.964
I have an idea of what
you and your sister have in mind.

40:55.171 --> 40:57.339
I'll just give this to my lawyer.

41:02.963 --> 41:04.130
Okay, well...

41:05.963 --> 41:08.172
there's nothing else
to talk about then, I guess.

41:13.046 --> 41:14.630
Okay, good night, Leonor.

41:29.546 --> 41:32.755
(TV SOUNDS)

41:34.963 --> 41:36.714
KATHY: Brian, can you give me a hand here?

41:37.379 --> 41:38.630
I have to call a patient.

41:40.379 --> 41:41.880
Give me a moment. Is Jake here?

41:42.338 --> 41:43.297
Yeah.

41:45.754 --> 41:46.797
(VIDEO GAME SOUNDS)

41:47.046 --> 41:48.589
- JAKE: Hi, Dad!
- TONY: Hi, Mr. J.

41:48.879 --> 41:50.130
BRIAN: Jake, you know it's a week night.

41:50.338 --> 41:51.714
What are you doing playing video games?

41:52.046 --> 41:54.839
- Can Tony stay and eat with us?
- BRIAN: No.

41:56.171 --> 41:59.047
Well, why not? He wanted to ask you
about your acting career.

41:59.296 --> 42:01.297
That's enough for tonight.
Just turn this thing off.

42:01.546 --> 42:03.089
- JAKE: Dad, come on.
- I said no!

42:03.338 --> 42:04.589
We're not even finished with this level.

42:05.046 --> 42:06.589
Tony, you need to go home now.

42:07.171 --> 42:08.589
We can talk about acting some other time.

42:09.004 --> 42:10.089
TONY: Sure, Mr. J.

42:13.046 --> 42:14.630
Your mom's waiting for you downstairs.

42:18.546 --> 42:19.797
KATHY: Did you ask your mother?

42:20.379 --> 42:21.672
TONY: She loves when Jake comes over.

42:21.963 --> 42:24.255
- Please, Mom? Please?
- Jake, I just made dinner.

42:24.463 --> 42:26.297
I'll eat it tomorrow for lunch, I promise.

42:27.463 --> 42:29.422
Okay, but I want you back here
in the morning.

42:29.629 --> 42:31.464
- Yes. Thanks, Mom.
- Thank you, Mrs. Jardine.

42:44.338 --> 42:46.922
- Please, Mami?
- No, Antonio.

42:47.213 --> 42:49.089
Come on, Ma,
we got spaghetti in the fridge.

42:49.338 --> 42:53.630
(IN SPANISH) No, Antonio, when I said
"no," I mean it. Don't ask me again.

42:54.129 --> 42:57.455
- It'll be super quiet, aren't we, Jake?
- Oh, yes, we're gonna be very quiet.

42:57.596 --> 43:00.297
(IN SPANISH) No, Antonio, don't insist!

43:04.629 --> 43:06.422
It's okay, Tony, I'll see you tomorrow.

43:06.879 --> 43:07.839
Yeah.

43:10.046 --> 43:12.839
- LEONOR: Good night, Jake.
- JAKE: Good night, Mrs. Calvelli.

43:13.129 --> 43:15.630
- I'll see you tomorrow.
- JAKE: See you tomorrow.

43:18.338 --> 43:21.922
(SIREN SOUNDS IN THE DISTANCE)

43:37.046 --> 43:37.839
TONY: Yo!

43:42.171 --> 43:43.255
Hey!

43:52.963 --> 43:55.339
Hey, I'm not talking to my mother anymore.

43:55.629 --> 43:56.505
Why not?

43:56.962 --> 43:59.963
- She said you can't come over.
- Why doesn't she want me over?

44:00.212 --> 44:01.338
I don't know.

44:05.004 --> 44:06.838
I don't think your dad wants me
around anymore either.

44:07.129 --> 44:09.005
He may be too chicken
to tell you, but I can tell.

44:09.212 --> 44:10.422
Why are they so mad at us?

44:10.629 --> 44:13.088
Our parents are involved
in a business matter,

44:13.296 --> 44:15.297
and it's getting ugly,
so they're taking it out on us.

44:19.171 --> 44:21.005
You're right, my dad was very cold to you.

44:22.879 --> 44:24.505
I won't talk to my parents, then, either.

44:25.171 --> 44:28.422
- TONY: Really?
- Really. Not unless they apologize.

44:28.837 --> 44:30.630
It's not gonna be easy.
You sure you can handle it?

44:31.379 --> 44:34.172
- I can handle it.
- You're a great friend, Jake.

44:34.879 --> 44:35.880
JAKE: You too.

44:39.296 --> 44:40.172
(DOOR OPENS)

44:40.379 --> 44:41.338
BRIAN: Hey.

44:43.296 --> 44:45.297
Did something happen
with Leonor downstairs?

44:48.046 --> 44:51.838
The store's closed,
but it's not even five.

44:56.629 --> 44:57.838
Have you seen Tony?

45:00.546 --> 45:01.505
Jake...

45:03.212 --> 45:05.172
can you stop joking around for a minute?

45:09.004 --> 45:11.713
Did you see if the store was
open earlier when you came home?

45:13.046 --> 45:14.255
Was it open?

45:15.462 --> 45:17.588
No, it wasn't?

45:24.129 --> 45:25.338
Jake, talk to me.

45:26.462 --> 45:29.297
(PHONE RINGS)

45:31.046 --> 45:33.463
Audrey, hi.

45:35.879 --> 45:38.088
No, no, I haven't heard from her.

45:39.504 --> 45:41.963
Today I got home early
and the store was closed.

45:43.212 --> 45:46.088
I feel responsible. We are responsible.

45:46.296 --> 45:48.422
Audrey will tell you if
she thinks you owe her money.

45:48.712 --> 45:51.338
- Don't worry about it.
- Well, she sort of did already.

45:52.587 --> 45:54.338
- What?
- Yeah.

45:54.546 --> 45:57.047
She told me
we owe her money for the store.

45:58.212 --> 45:59.505
- KATHY: Incredible.
- BRIAN: Yeah.

46:02.004 --> 46:03.422
KATHY: Jake, did you see Leonor today?

46:07.212 --> 46:08.463
Still not talking?

46:09.504 --> 46:10.422
No.

46:13.462 --> 46:15.505
You can't go on
like this forever, you know.

46:23.712 --> 46:26.672
TONY: You look like you've been
doing this acting thing for a long time.

46:26.879 --> 46:27.797
Really?

46:28.004 --> 46:31.255
When you did the Emotional Recall
exercise, it seemed so natural.

46:32.046 --> 46:34.005
My father was a stunt man
when I was a kid,

46:34.212 --> 46:36.172
so I spent a lot of time
on sets and stuff.

46:36.879 --> 46:38.463
TONY: Oh, so you've been
doing this forever.

46:38.879 --> 46:41.838
Well, no, because when I was
eight years old, he died.

46:42.504 --> 46:43.838
TONY: Did he die doing a stunt?

46:44.212 --> 46:47.338
- No, he had throat cancer.
- TONY: Oh.

46:48.504 --> 46:49.838
I'm sorry for your loss.

46:51.129 --> 46:52.088
GIRL: Thanks.

46:53.212 --> 46:55.172
- I'll see you later?
- I hope so.

47:04.629 --> 47:07.505
TONY: Hey. You know anyone
with a swimming pool?

47:08.129 --> 47:09.005
No, why?

47:09.296 --> 47:11.255
I would kill to see her in a bathing suit.

47:11.504 --> 47:14.588
- Could you imagine?
- I never thought about that.

47:16.171 --> 47:18.255
So, who do you like, huh?

47:19.962 --> 47:22.755
- They're all nice.
- You can tell me, you know.

47:23.379 --> 47:26.338
- Tell you what?
- If you like someone.

47:28.129 --> 47:30.796
- I don't know.
- That's what you always say.

47:31.295 --> 47:33.171
Well, I do have an idea you might like.

47:33.629 --> 47:34.838
Yeah? What's that?

47:37.129 --> 47:38.713
Eva talked about going dancing.

47:39.212 --> 47:42.421
There's a matinee club,
like after hours, for kids.

47:42.754 --> 47:45.505
- When?
- Sunday afternoon in the city.

47:47.170 --> 47:49.338
- Let's go!
- Would be fun, wouldn't it?

47:49.545 --> 47:51.838
That would be great,
if I could just dance with her.

47:55.962 --> 47:57.713
Wow, Jake, that's actually getting good.

47:58.045 --> 48:00.421
- I'm impressed.
- Thank you.

48:04.337 --> 48:06.421
(SEWING MACHINE WHIRS)

48:06.962 --> 48:08.838
BIANCA: Hi, can I help you?

48:09.129 --> 48:11.630
Thank you, I want to talk to Leonor.

48:16.504 --> 48:18.921
- Hi, Leonor.
- Hi.

48:19.962 --> 48:22.588
Just a second, let me finish this.

48:24.504 --> 48:26.255
(SEWING MACHINE STOPS)

48:29.129 --> 48:30.463
You're home early.

48:31.129 --> 48:32.088
Monday.

48:33.170 --> 48:35.130
That's right, your day off.

48:38.379 --> 48:39.630
KATHY: That's a cute dress.

48:41.129 --> 48:42.255
I made it.

48:44.129 --> 48:45.421
Leonor, do you have a minute?

48:46.629 --> 48:50.421
LEONOR: I have to finish this
for a client tonight.

48:52.462 --> 48:54.255
KATHY: Tony still not talking?

48:55.379 --> 48:57.338
Not a word to me yesterday.

48:58.004 --> 49:00.588
- Same with Jake.
- LEONOR: It's very annoying.

49:01.545 --> 49:05.671
One good thing, I have to say is that Jake
is painting and drawing more than ever.

49:06.337 --> 49:07.463
LEONOR: Is that good?

49:07.879 --> 49:12.838
Yeah, if he really wants to go to LaGuardia,
he has to put together a portfolio.

49:13.212 --> 49:14.130
Mm.

49:14.379 --> 49:17.505
KATHY: Is Tony still thinking
of applying also?

49:18.004 --> 49:19.130
How would I know?

49:20.004 --> 49:22.838
It's been four days.
He hasn't said a word to me.

49:24.629 --> 49:26.088
KATHY: Listen, Leonor, you know that

49:26.337 --> 49:29.921
I am trained in conflict resolution,
and I'm hoping to help here,

49:30.170 --> 49:34.005
to help settle this problem
between you and our family.

49:36.379 --> 49:38.755
LEONOR: Has your husband
asked you to do this?

49:40.295 --> 49:41.130
No.

49:42.504 --> 49:44.713
KATHY: By the way,
he's been working very hard.

49:45.129 --> 49:47.463
I'm not sure you know,
but he's rehearsing a new play.

49:48.462 --> 49:51.505
No. I haven't seen your husband.

49:52.045 --> 49:54.171
(SEWING MACHINE WHIRS)

49:54.462 --> 49:57.463
I know he's been waiting to hear from you.

49:57.712 --> 49:59.255
(SEWING MACHINE STOPS)

50:01.545 --> 50:02.546
Leonor?

50:03.629 --> 50:04.505
LEONOR: Not here.

50:14.212 --> 50:18.505
KATHY: I know you think we're the rich
people coming into this neighborhood,

50:19.462 --> 50:22.963
but the truth is Brian hasn't
made any money in years.

50:23.962 --> 50:26.421
I've been supporting our family
with my hard work.

50:27.129 --> 50:29.921
- That's not my problem.
- KATHY: I know it's not.

50:30.962 --> 50:34.755
What I want to tell you is that we will
give you time, but we need this money.

50:36.045 --> 50:37.921
We need the shop to cover its rent.

50:40.004 --> 50:41.963
Not an unfair thing to ask of a tenant.

50:48.962 --> 50:50.463
The woman is trouble, Brian.

50:51.879 --> 50:55.838
Once again, our warm,
lovable, unwise father

50:56.128 --> 50:59.129
has left us a big mess
and no instructions.

51:01.128 --> 51:04.004
I think that we should start
the eviction process right away.

51:05.462 --> 51:07.088
I don't wanna have to do that.

51:08.462 --> 51:09.921
It takes a while, you know.

51:11.003 --> 51:12.588
I just don't want this to get ugly.

51:14.545 --> 51:16.171
The boys are best friends now.

51:18.378 --> 51:21.254
Just remember our dad worked
hard to leave us something,

51:21.503 --> 51:27.088
and now you have this nice big apartment
to live in, and I'm getting nothing.

51:30.545 --> 51:32.004
Just give me a little more time.

51:34.045 --> 51:36.171
I can't really do this without you, Brian.

51:40.003 --> 51:42.421
(DANCE MUSIC PLAYS)

53:44.295 --> 53:46.504
Hey, do you want to come
to the beach with me?

53:46.962 --> 53:48.588
- EVA: Huh?
- TONY: The beach!

53:49.045 --> 53:50.463
You, me.

53:52.128 --> 53:53.463
Yes? No?

53:53.878 --> 53:57.963
No, Tony, you're really nice
and everything, but I'm into older guys.

54:02.128 --> 54:03.088
Oh.

54:06.337 --> 54:08.421
- Thank you for being honest.
- EVA: What?

54:09.462 --> 54:11.338
Thank you for being honest!

55:30.003 --> 55:31.754
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

55:46.836 --> 55:48.879
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

56:45.753 --> 56:47.337
She doesn't acknowledge the lease,

56:48.045 --> 56:52.462
she doesn't try and negotiate,
she has no plans on leaving.

56:52.878 --> 56:55.087
Now she's actually hiring new people.

56:55.336 --> 56:58.462
(SIGHS) I told you
this was not gonna be easy.

57:01.211 --> 57:03.212
Audrey wants to start an eviction process.

57:04.170 --> 57:07.462
She's got a lawyer ready to go already.

57:11.628 --> 57:12.587
Good.

57:14.503 --> 57:15.837
So it's decided.

57:21.128 --> 57:22.129
Is it?

57:27.003 --> 57:28.296
Who's gonna tell Jake?

57:32.045 --> 57:33.004
I'll do it.

57:33.961 --> 57:34.962
It's my problem.

57:37.128 --> 57:38.171
Do it soon.

57:40.295 --> 57:41.296
Please?

57:58.211 --> 57:59.337
WOMAN: What are you writing?

58:01.378 --> 58:03.962
An idea for a short story.

58:05.544 --> 58:10.170
A young girl grows up on the shores
of a lake, as you have done.

58:11.003 --> 58:14.504
She loves the lake, as the gulls do

58:15.378 --> 58:18.795
and she is as free
and as happy as they are.

58:20.628 --> 58:24.254
But a man sees her, who
happens to come by that way...

58:25.878 --> 58:30.587
and he destroys her out of idleness,
as this seagull here has been destroyed.

58:31.169 --> 58:33.629
WOMAN: Boris! Where are you?

58:34.378 --> 58:35.629
BRIAN: I'm coming this minute!

58:37.211 --> 58:38.504
What do you want?

58:39.169 --> 58:42.337
We are not going away after all!

59:02.128 --> 59:03.504
WOMAN: It is a dream!

59:06.044 --> 59:08.337
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS)

59:27.503 --> 59:28.629
So?

59:35.544 --> 59:38.295
Did you understand why
Nina says she's the seagull?

59:47.544 --> 59:50.754
KATHY: Jake, it's your father's
opening night.

01:00:02.003 --> 01:00:04.254
You two ever think about anybody
other than yourselves?

01:00:05.961 --> 01:00:06.920
Huh?

01:00:08.503 --> 01:00:10.087
Say something, Jake!

01:00:11.961 --> 01:00:13.170
(SHOUTS) Say something!

01:00:15.544 --> 01:00:17.670
One of the hardest things
to realize when you're a child

01:00:17.878 --> 01:00:19.837
is that your parents are people too,
you understand that?

01:00:20.378 --> 01:00:23.712
They care about things.
They make mistakes.

01:00:24.211 --> 01:00:26.587
But they try to do what they think
is the right thing to do.

01:00:26.794 --> 01:00:29.337
Does any of what I'm saying
make any sense to you?

01:00:29.794 --> 01:00:32.295
- (GIGGLING)
- What's so funny, Tony?

01:00:33.294 --> 01:00:34.254
Huh?

01:00:35.003 --> 01:00:36.587
Why don't you tell me,
what's so funny, Tony?

01:00:36.836 --> 01:00:38.754
You think you got it in you
to be an actor?

01:00:39.544 --> 01:00:41.087
Take one rejection after another?

01:00:41.294 --> 01:00:43.254
We'll see how you react when
you don't get into LaGuardia!

01:00:43.503 --> 01:00:44.920
- We'll just see then!
- KATHY: Brian!

01:00:45.128 --> 01:00:46.170
BRIAN: Goddamn it!

01:01:05.961 --> 01:01:08.787
Also try to arrange them by color or tone.

01:01:09.003 --> 01:01:13.129
I usually like to start with lighter colors
in the front, and end with the darker ones.

01:01:13.628 --> 01:01:15.420
Black goes in the back.

01:01:17.128 --> 01:01:18.837
Hello, can we help you?

01:01:19.503 --> 01:01:21.587
Oh, it's okay, Valentina, it's for me.

01:01:22.836 --> 01:01:25.962
He is Brian Jardine, our neighbor.

01:01:26.377 --> 01:01:29.837
- He's a great actor.
- Oh, have I seen you in anything?

01:01:30.461 --> 01:01:33.170
- I doubt it.
- He's in a new play.

01:01:33.377 --> 01:01:36.003
- What is it called?
- <i>The Seagull.</i>

01:01:36.211 --> 01:01:39.253
Oh, that must be very popular.

01:01:42.002 --> 01:01:46.295
Can you give me
five minutes alone, please?

01:02:14.544 --> 01:02:17.837
The day your father died,

01:02:19.752 --> 01:02:21.253
he came by in the morning.

01:02:22.627 --> 01:02:26.628
And I asked him to buy me
a pack of cigarettes.

01:02:30.002 --> 01:02:32.003
And I never saw him again.

01:02:38.169 --> 01:02:40.337
He cared about me, Brian.

01:02:41.169 --> 01:02:42.628
Can you believe that?

01:02:45.127 --> 01:02:46.337
Every day we'd...

01:02:48.169 --> 01:02:50.753
talk and share things.

01:02:54.961 --> 01:02:56.920
Have you ever had a friend like that?

01:02:57.169 --> 01:02:59.503
Someone you can tell anything?

01:03:02.502 --> 01:03:03.753
Only my wife.

01:03:06.627 --> 01:03:08.503
I'm a lot like Jake, I...

01:03:11.002 --> 01:03:13.087
It's never been easy for me to have...

01:03:14.377 --> 01:03:16.837
(SIGHS) close friends.

01:03:18.627 --> 01:03:19.795
I hope...

01:03:21.461 --> 01:03:23.337
that you can understand

01:03:24.127 --> 01:03:26.837
that what's happening is nothing personal.

01:03:30.127 --> 01:03:32.503
I can't pay three times...

01:03:33.544 --> 01:03:35.337
what I paid to your father.

01:03:37.627 --> 01:03:39.628
It's not possible.

01:03:41.461 --> 01:03:42.962
I can't survive.

01:03:47.294 --> 01:03:50.503
I thought you were in a new big play.

01:03:52.211 --> 01:03:56.295
I am in a new play, but it's not big,

01:03:57.336 --> 01:03:59.003
and it's not a lot of money.

01:04:00.502 --> 01:04:02.587
It's just the way that it is, Leonor.

01:04:03.836 --> 01:04:07.712
I'm fortunate that my father
left me a house in Brooklyn.

01:04:08.294 --> 01:04:11.253
He wanted me to stay here. He told me so.

01:04:11.461 --> 01:04:16.920
And I also have a sister, and she has
a family too, and we have to decide

01:04:17.169 --> 01:04:21.003
what to do about this together.
It's not just up to me.

01:04:22.002 --> 01:04:24.087
You know, your father thought your sister

01:04:24.294 --> 01:04:27.212
was the one who inherited his brains.

01:04:31.461 --> 01:04:33.462
I'm sure he'd agree with Audrey...

01:04:34.836 --> 01:04:36.170
that above all else...

01:04:39.127 --> 01:04:40.753
it's important to take care of business.

01:04:41.002 --> 01:04:42.837
No, he wouldn't have.

01:04:44.002 --> 01:04:45.170
I can promise you.

01:04:45.877 --> 01:04:47.420
What do you want me to say, Leonor?

01:04:48.044 --> 01:04:50.295
I have a family. We have bills, too.

01:04:51.461 --> 01:04:57.795
Do you know why your father didn't come
to your son's birthday, the last one?

01:04:58.627 --> 01:04:59.628
BRIAN: He had the flu.

01:05:00.502 --> 01:05:02.961
Maybe that's what he told you.

01:05:03.460 --> 01:05:06.711
The truth is he was embarrassed

01:05:07.335 --> 01:05:10.836
that everything in your house
was paid for by your wife.

01:05:11.960 --> 01:05:14.170
He thought you should be more of a man.

01:05:19.127 --> 01:05:20.128
Well...

01:05:23.960 --> 01:05:25.461
he's not around anymore...

01:05:27.377 --> 01:05:28.420
is he?

01:05:30.169 --> 01:05:31.836
He's certainly not.

01:05:51.960 --> 01:05:55.836
(IN SPANISH) Unfortunately, it's a clause
that's common in any commercial contract.

01:06:05.794 --> 01:06:06.753
(SIGHS)

01:06:09.960 --> 01:06:11.836
(IN SPANISH) What am I going to do?

01:06:12.176 --> 01:06:14.433
I can't afford this.

01:06:15.112 --> 01:06:17.127
I told you not to go outside.

01:06:17.250 --> 01:06:19.679
I told you not to go outside, Antonio!

01:06:20.986 --> 01:06:24.121
I am up to here with this game of yours.

01:06:26.044 --> 01:06:27.628
HERNÁN: I'm sorry, Leo.

01:06:30.169 --> 01:06:33.253
Where do they get this number?

01:06:33.669 --> 01:06:35.761
HERNÁN: It's a penalty.

01:06:35.961 --> 01:06:40.233
It's a penalty for overstaying.
That's why it's in the contract.

01:06:49.127 --> 01:06:50.728
And there's nothing we can do?

01:06:52.169 --> 01:06:55.228
HERNÁN: I've done everything I can.
There's nothing to do.

01:06:59.036 --> 01:07:01.183
You have one week.

01:07:03.119 --> 01:07:05.571
One week to leave this place.

01:07:12.294 --> 01:07:15.253
(SOBS)

01:07:18.544 --> 01:07:19.586
TONY: Mami?

01:07:53.544 --> 01:07:57.836
TONY: Hello, Mr. J. Is, um... Jake home?

01:07:59.627 --> 01:08:00.628
BRIAN: Yes.

01:08:01.502 --> 01:08:03.003
He's doing his homework.

01:08:04.294 --> 01:08:07.253
TONY: Um, I'd like to talk
to him, if I could.

01:08:10.294 --> 01:08:11.420
BRIAN: Of course.

01:08:12.960 --> 01:08:15.461
Come in. Why don't you
both come in, please?

01:08:31.292 --> 01:08:33.752
KATHY: Are you sure we can't
get you something, Leonor?

01:08:36.377 --> 01:08:38.919
I'm fine, thanks.

01:08:41.127 --> 01:08:41.961
(DOOR BURSTS OPEN)

01:08:42.167 --> 01:08:44.169
- JAKE: Mom!
- KATHY: What's going on?

01:08:44.377 --> 01:08:47.252
Mom, Tony told me Leonor's
being evacuated from the store!

01:08:47.502 --> 01:08:49.919
KATHY: It's not "evacuated,"
it's "evicted."

01:08:50.167 --> 01:08:52.636
How could you do that?
How could you do that to them?

01:08:52.792 --> 01:08:54.294
It's a terrible situation.

01:08:54.752 --> 01:08:57.294
The rent is too expensive!
She can't afford it, Mom.

01:08:57.542 --> 01:09:00.169
So Dad just needs to give her
a discount or something so she can.

01:09:00.460 --> 01:09:02.461
Your mother and I tried to
talk to you about this, Jake.

01:09:02.752 --> 01:09:03.794
This not talking didn't help.

01:09:04.002 --> 01:09:06.336
- KATHY: Don't blame this on him.
- It's okay, I'm talking now.

01:09:07.127 --> 01:09:08.919
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
I'll never do that again.

01:09:09.127 --> 01:09:11.336
- I promise, Dad, I promise.
- Calm down. Jake, calm down.

01:09:11.542 --> 01:09:14.836
- But I have a great idea...
- Listen to me. Your Grandpa Max,

01:09:15.127 --> 01:09:17.627
he didn't just leave this house
for the three of us here.

01:09:17.835 --> 01:09:20.294
No, I know, he loved Leonor, too.
Tony told me!

01:09:20.502 --> 01:09:24.919
BRIAN: Of course he liked Leonor, but he
left it for us and for your Aunt Audrey.

01:09:25.167 --> 01:09:28.127
But I have a great idea.
We go back to our old apartment,

01:09:28.335 --> 01:09:30.586
and we rent this place and give
the money to Aunt Audrey.

01:09:31.167 --> 01:09:33.086
Tony and I are both going to be going

01:09:33.292 --> 01:09:35.836
to the LaGuardia High School for
Performing Arts in Manhattan,

01:09:36.292 --> 01:09:38.669
so I don't need to take the
subway or anything to school.

01:09:38.835 --> 01:09:42.169
I could just walk.
And you'll be closer to the theater.

01:09:43.335 --> 01:09:46.252
I loved the show, Dad,
I loved it. I really did.

01:09:46.460 --> 01:09:49.836
Tony did, too. We both talked
about it a lot afterwards.

01:09:50.502 --> 01:09:54.127
And I thought you were really good, and I
thought it was really complex and everything.

01:09:54.877 --> 01:09:58.503
I'm sorry I didn't tell you then,
I'm sorry, but I really liked it, I did.

01:10:01.668 --> 01:10:02.628
(SOBS)

01:10:03.002 --> 01:10:04.169
BRIAN: (WHISPERS) Okay, okay.

01:10:06.502 --> 01:10:07.503
Okay.

01:10:16.960 --> 01:10:18.836
(KIDS SHOUTING)

01:11:00.043 --> 01:11:02.086
(KIDS PLAYING)

01:11:39.502 --> 01:11:41.253
(SUBWAY PASSES)

01:12:39.460 --> 01:12:40.586
Mr. Jardine?

01:12:41.376 --> 01:12:43.919
- Where were you, son?
- I'm sorry, Dad.

01:12:50.460 --> 01:12:52.961
You still have a lot to do
to finish your portfolio?

01:12:53.460 --> 01:12:56.169
JAKE: I just need to finish one more
painting, and then I'm done.

01:12:57.876 --> 01:12:59.336
That's what you said last week.

01:13:00.168 --> 01:13:02.002
You just had to finish one more painting.

01:13:02.293 --> 01:13:03.711
I want them to be good.

01:13:07.376 --> 01:13:10.961
Do you remember, by any chance,
a story about my friend Tina?

01:13:11.960 --> 01:13:14.586
The one that sold her hair
in India for a train ticket?

01:13:15.001 --> 01:13:17.086
No, that was Martine.

01:13:17.335 --> 01:13:20.294
Tina was a girl I went to
high school with, she was a...

01:13:20.793 --> 01:13:23.461
Oh. She was a dancer.

01:13:24.376 --> 01:13:28.461
And her mother was a dancer. She was
literally born to be a dancer.

01:13:29.626 --> 01:13:33.586
And during high school, she got
into a really good conservatory,

01:13:34.210 --> 01:13:37.419
and I saw her a couple of times
after that, and

01:13:37.626 --> 01:13:40.627
she was always getting ready
to get this or gonna get that.

01:13:41.210 --> 01:13:43.461
Each time, her arm would be in a sling,

01:13:44.126 --> 01:13:46.419
or she would be on crutches.

01:13:46.835 --> 01:13:50.794
And the last time I saw her,
I ran into her on the subway.

01:13:51.501 --> 01:13:53.461
It was clear she hadn't danced in years.

01:13:53.876 --> 01:13:55.419
She was completely out of shape.

01:13:55.626 --> 01:13:58.294
You would have never imagined
that this was the same girl.

01:14:00.335 --> 01:14:01.836
Gee, thanks, Dad.

01:14:02.626 --> 01:14:04.586
That's a very encouraging story.

01:14:05.126 --> 01:14:06.627
Why didn't Tina go very far?

01:14:07.876 --> 01:14:10.169
- I don't know.
- She trained too hard.

01:14:11.335 --> 01:14:12.294
Huh?

01:14:13.043 --> 01:14:14.461
She practiced too much.

01:14:15.460 --> 01:14:18.252
She didn't just trust
her natural abilities.

01:14:18.793 --> 01:14:22.294
Jake, you're gonna meet a lot of
really talented people in your life,

01:14:22.501 --> 01:14:25.086
and they're not all
gonna be suited to be artists.

01:14:25.960 --> 01:14:28.252
They're not all gonna
have the brains to know

01:14:28.460 --> 01:14:30.252
when to insist and when to...

01:14:31.960 --> 01:14:33.086
to stop.

01:14:33.960 --> 01:14:37.961
When to push themselves
and when to just relax.

01:14:39.501 --> 01:14:41.961
Most of them won't all have that balance.

01:14:42.835 --> 01:14:44.669
And how do I know if I have the balance?

01:14:45.960 --> 01:14:48.002
That's why I'm telling you this, because

01:14:48.501 --> 01:14:50.461
you're turning in your portfolio soon.

01:14:51.168 --> 01:14:52.502
And they're gonna love it.

01:14:54.293 --> 01:14:55.502
I know they are.

01:14:58.460 --> 01:14:59.919
And they're gonna love you.

01:15:02.376 --> 01:15:04.002
And you're gonna go to LaGuardia.

01:15:06.210 --> 01:15:07.711
And you're gonna have fun...

01:15:08.960 --> 01:15:10.461
and some challenges, too.

01:15:12.126 --> 01:15:14.961
But soon enough, you're gonna
find out if you have that balance.

01:15:20.168 --> 01:15:22.002
Do you know if Tony's still applying?

01:15:23.834 --> 01:15:26.169
I don't know,
I don't know what he's doing.

01:15:29.209 --> 01:15:30.127
(BRIAN SIGHS)

01:15:30.293 --> 01:15:32.419
BRIAN: Well, I wish I had
handled that differently, son.

01:15:32.959 --> 01:15:36.835
- What do you mean?
- BRIAN: Just Tony and his mom.

01:15:38.168 --> 01:15:42.335
I wish I had told you earlier
what was going on.

01:15:43.126 --> 01:15:44.627
Would it have changed anything?

01:15:46.459 --> 01:15:47.460
No.

01:15:49.043 --> 01:15:50.252
Probably not.

01:15:51.459 --> 01:15:52.585
But still.

01:16:11.293 --> 01:16:15.002
Dad, would you mind
if I played one of my video games?

01:16:15.834 --> 01:16:16.919
Would that be okay?

01:16:20.001 --> 01:16:21.085
BRIAN: Of course.

01:16:23.209 --> 01:16:25.169
Will Mom be okay with it?

01:16:29.459 --> 01:16:30.502
BRIAN: I think so.

